Finally made it to the downtown location.  I had one of the daily specials, but I can't remember the name of it. It was a HUGE scoop of chicken salad on top of a HUGE salad that didn't skimp on the raspberries, blueberries and pecans. Mom had a cup of chili that she said had just the right bite of flavor without being too spicy while my husband enjoyed his buffalo chicken wrap with cole slaw. We got in just in time because the place really filled up by 1:00.  It's a nice place to stop in for a bite that's not too heavy while strolling around town.

Disappointed today. We are long time patrons of NEThyme. Lately both locations have been slipping in our book. 3 of us visited the Main St location on a beautiful sunny Saturday for lunch as our 25 year old son had never been there and we had told him that it was better than their Halcyon location. My wife ordered quiche and a salad, but the young lady at the register said they were out of her beloved creamy basil dressing... so she switched her order to a grouper fingers special featuring a basil tarter sauce only to find out when served that they were out of the tarter sauce too! My son's NET Jumble brunch came with a large but absolutely stone cold biscuit with potatoes in the dish that were not cooked through. My 1/2 roast beef sandwich with a cup of clam chowder was fine, the only saving grace of our orders. Why and how does a usually well run restaurant run out of house-made dressings and tarter sauce before lunch service is even over? And to serve cold biscuits and partially uncooked breakfast potatoes is completely out of order. I believe we will give them a few months to themselves before we return for a retry so hopefully these issues will be well ironed out!

My kids ate chicken fingers and fries and mac and cheese. All tasted homemade and super good. The fries were especially good and came with a yummy kid friendly dipping sauce (something BBQ?) The place was nice but food was really EXPENSIVE. We ate at different places in downtown Alpharetta so we know what to expect but the portion of food that we got was utterly small for the price.  I got chicken piccata ($15) and Brussels  sprouts. ($4). The Brussels sprouts was really good. But I got 3 tiny chicken pieces (my 2 y/o son’s palm size). My husband got a sandwich and he said the same thing that it was so small, not much meat in it. I got a drink, it was ok, nothing special.
Good food

My husband and I went here for a quick bite on a Friday and sat at the bar. Service was perfect and the drinks were fantastic, I had the Manhattan with orange and it may be my new favorite! For a Friday we were in and out pretty quick but not rushed and the overall atmosphere was great. We will be back! The menu has so many other things I want to try!

The short version: disappointing. The long version: I came here with my parents, wanting to try something new. We each got a sandwich, a side, and a fountain drink. It cost 54 dollars. Nothing was bad, but nothing was exceptionally good either. The Corned Beef Reuben and Pastrami were basic sandwiches, nothing special. The Garlic Mashed Potatoes didn't taste at all like garlic - just simple mashed potatoes seasoned with salt. The mac and cheese was pasta shells in a watery, vaguely-creamy sauce with what tasted like crumbled Ritz crackers on top. Some of the Brussels sprouts were burnt. The restaurant itself was nice; it was clean and spacious but felt cozy. The service was good, and the employees were friendly. Again, nothing was necessarily bad. Everything was mediocre, the kind of food you could get at deli, pub, or sandwich shops, but extraordinarily expensive. A return is unlikely.
Unfortunately the food was slow and cold. Nice location with good potential though.

Love this place for weekday lunch.  The food always exceeds my expectations.  Amazing soups, salads, and sandwiches.  The chick salad is stupid good.  I might be able to eat the caprese salad every day!  Highly recommended!!!

I think this place have potential, but there is some issues I have with the way they do their food. I know that sounds confusing. I'll explain what I mean. The first time I went here for around a month or so ago. I ordered the shrimp po boy they had on special. When I ordered the sandwich the waitress asked me what kind of bread would I like on the sandwich. I was puzzled because traditionally on a French roll. They don't offer this. They have a barrage of breads but not that one. I got it on ciabatta. I thought to myself blasphemous, but I was hungry so what the hell. The flavor of the po boy was good in spite of the ciabatta. I got the pesto pasta salad as my side. It was ok but don't understand why they put these huge rectangular blocks of cheese in it. I think it is a little too much for the salad. All in all, it was an ok experience and thought maybe I should give it another try. I went again today and got a margarita to drink. Do not get the margarita. I repeat. Do not get the margarita. Ironically,  the po boy was on special again. I decided to get the roast beef au jus which in layman's terms is a French dip. I ordered it and the same decision with the bread came up. This annoyed me because if you are going to serve traditional sandwiches that many have had the same way consistently let's keep it traditional. The atmosphere is nice and the people are friendly. I think this place would be good if they got this aspects of their menu fixed.
Went for Sunday brunch, food was great, nice atmosphere
Lovely Main Street Cafe... creative menu, good food.. great staff....

I ordered the vegetable plate to go. The description shows several vegetables listed  so I thought that it would be healthy and light. When I got home and opened the packaging for the dish, I was very disappointed. First of all, this dish in no shape, form, or fashion worth the $8.95 + tax that they charged. Second of all,  the vegetable plate did not include all of the vegetables listed in the description and some vegetables that were included were old and over cooked. Thirdly, the dish looked like slop to me. It was about four vegetables (two of them potatoes) all cooked together on a flat top (from what I could discern). The potatoes were burnt, greasy, and the rest of the mixture was just a dry lump of overcooked / old veggies. I could not eat it..Why don't they just offer a normal vegetable plate with a variety of vegetables individually cooked and take this concoction /slop off of the menu (looks like scraps from plates that need to be thrown out). Who knows..maybe that is what I was served (i.e. scraps).  I visited this restaurant several years back at their Mcginnis Ferry location. At the time, I had only a salad. At the time the salad was not bad...but then again it would take a complete idiot to mess up a salad...maybe I should have just gotten a salad....but what I was served look like scraps. I was highly disappointed and won't be back...
